I would like to ignore JS files in my project when there's a matching TS _or_ matching TSX file.  Right now I have to choose one or the other.  Please support making the "when" directive in the "files.exclude" workspace setting use a regex, so I could do this:

``` javascript
{
  "files.exclude": {
        "**/*.js": { "when": "$(basename).tsx?"},
  }
}
```

I'm looking at having DustJS files syntax highlighted. It's just like PHP/ASP/etc, where it's an HTML file, with another language mixed in.

Is this supported? I'm not getting any highlighting for HTML in my file. There are no errors in the console either.

I created an extension using `yo code` and selecting `New Language Support`. I then used this URL as the tmLanguage file. https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jimmyhchan/Dustjs.tmbundle/master/Syntaxes/DustJS.tmLanguage This language has an include for `text.html.basic`. 

When doing a search in this repo for `text.html.basic` I get several other syntaxes that reference it. If I try using those languages with an html or dust file, it doesn't highlight the html. If I change the language to html, everything highlights as expected.

This is my package.json file. The tmLanguage file is the one referenced above.

``` json
{
    "name": "dustjs",
    "displayName": "dustjs",
    "description": "dustjs language support",
    "version": "0.0.1",
    "publisher": "anonymous",
    "engines": {
        "vscode": "^0.10.1"
    },
    "categories": [
        "Languages"
    ],
    "contributes": {
        "languages": [{
            "id": "dustjs",
            "aliases": ["DustJS", "dustjs"],
            "extensions": [".dust",".tl",".dustjs"],
            "configuration": "./dustjs.configuration.json"
        }],
        "grammars": [{
            "language": "dustjs",
            "scopeName": "text.html.dustjs",
            "path": "./syntaxes/dustjs.tmLanguage"
        }]
    }
}
```

My extension is activated when code startup.

```
"activationEvents": [
    "*"
]
```

and the activate function like this 

```
export function activate() {
    vscode.workspace.onDidOpenTextDocument((d)=>{
        vscode.window.showInformationMessage("[Document Opened]:" + path.basename(d.fileName));
    });
}
```

But vscode never showInformationMessage when startup although there are a document opened at first.

I try to  use the `-logPluginHostCommunication` command line argument.

I find that `_acceptModelAdd` be called before `$activatePluginInPluginHost`

![1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7069719/11749753/884b301e-a06a-11e5-89e7-b09a2bc4b469.png)

so it's too late to listen `onDidOpenTextDocument` when my extension is activated.

